        <div class="faq-right">
            <div class="faq-accordion">
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How does Idaho tax federal retirement benefits?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Idaho doesn't tax Social Security benefits and offers a significant deduction for other retirement income ($52,070 for 2026 if 65+, $33,930 if under 65). This makes Idaho very tax-friendly for federal retirees compared to many other states.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">When should I retire from federal service in Idaho?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">Optimal timing depends on your years of service, age, financial needs, and health insurance considerations. You can retire at MRA with 30 years, age 60 with 20 years, or age 62 with 5 years. Earlier retirement may include a supplement but also pension reductions.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">How should I invest my TSP as an Idaho federal employee?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">TSP allocation should match your time horizon and risk tolerance. With 10+ years to retirement, most employees benefit from stock-heavy allocations (C, S, I Funds). The G Fund is too conservative for long-term growth, though appropriate for short-term needs.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">What happens to my health insurance if I retire early?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">You can continue FEHB in retirement if you've been enrolled for 5 years before retirement (or since your first opportunity to enroll). This is crucial for early retirees before Medicare eligibility. The government continues to pay 70-75% of premiums.</div>
                </button>
                <button class="faq-acc-item">
                    <span class="faq-acc-q">Should I roll my TSP to an IRA when I retire?</span>
                    <span class="faq-acc-icon">+</span>
                    <div class="faq-acc-a">TSP has very low fees and good investment options, but limited withdrawal flexibility. An IRA rollover provides more investment choices and withdrawal options but higher fees. We analyze your specific situation to recommend the best strategy — sometimes keeping some in TSP and rolling some to an IRA works best.</div>
                </button>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>